== Introduction == <!--T:83-->

<!--T:1-->

The solid modelling capabilities of FreeCAD are based on the [[OpenCASCADE|OpenCASCADE Technology]] (OCCT) kernel, a professional-grade CAD system that features advanced 3D geometry creation and manipulation. 

Conceptually the Part module provides an interface layer to the geometric primitives and functions of OCCT. In turn the Part module is used to expose these primitives and functions to the user through the use of workbenches. Workbenches serve as a way to collect and present these lower level functions to the user. Typically, workbenches consist of a collection for general purpose or application/discipline specific functions. Part workbench is an example of a general purpose workbench. (The BIM workbench is an example of an application or discipline specific workbench.)

<!--T:118-->
A comprehensive list of workbenches, both built in and external, can be found here: https://wiki.freecad.org/Workbenches

<!--T:35-->

There are two general purpose workbenches for basic 3D solid modeling; Part workbench and [[Image:Workbench_PartDesign.svg|24px]] [[PartDesign_Workbench|PartDesign]]. 

Part workbench provides a traditional [[Constructive_solid_geometry|constructive solid geometry]] (CSG) workflow. Each object created in Part workbench is an independent solid. They can be created from a parametrically defined sketch (See: [[Image:Workbench_Sketcher.svg|24px]] [[Sketcher_Workbench|Sketcher]]) using Part workbench tools like Extrude, Revolve, Loft, etc. In addition, basic primitives like Cube, Cylinder, etc. can be created as well. These objects can be combined, with Boolean operations, to create more complex solids.

The Part Workbench can also create create objects that are not solids, such as faces, shells and objects with only edges or vertices. It also provides a variety of other general purpose tools for geometry manipulation, geometry validation, and making copies.

[[PartDesign_Workbench|PartDesign Workbench]] provides a feature based workflow. Part Design creates only solids.

A more detailed discussion of Part workbench versus Part Design workbench can be found here: [[Part_and_PartDesign|Part and Part Design]].





